<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Willing To Talk With U.S. on War Debt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Willing To Talk With U.S. on War Debt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2605144094 Taipei CNA in English 1310 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2605144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 26 (CNA) -- Foreign Minister Fredrick 
C. Chien said Thursday [26 May] that Taiwan is sincere in 
negotiating with the United States in trying to settle a debt it 
has owed since World War II. 
  "However, we will not pay the debt without prudent 
consideration," Chien said while responding to a legislative 
query by Democratic Progressive Party legislator Yu Ling-ya. 
  Chien said the United States granted about US$1 billion in 
loans to the Republic of China [ROC] during the war, but that 
the ROC Government made huge expenditures for US troops 
stationed in Mainland China. Therefore, he said, to simply say 
the ROC owes the US the money would be unreasonable. 
  Taipei and Washington have since 1960 held several rounds of 
talks on the debt issue, but because of the difficulty in 
finding documents related to the debt, no conclusions have 
resulted. 
  Chien, however, said that Taiwan is still willing to discuss 
the issue with the United States in an effort to find a 
solution. "As long as the US wants us to talk, then we will 
talk," Chien said. 
  Several lawmakers have urged the government to reject US 
requests to pay the debt because the United States no longer 
recognizes the Republic of China. Instead, they say, the United 
States should turn to Mainland China to claim the debt. 

</TEXT>

