<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Views Disposal of Land Along Airport Railroad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Views Disposal of Land Along Airport Railroad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2705042094 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 
27 May 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> HK2705042094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Doreen Cheung in Beijing and Fung Wai-Kong] </F>
  [Text] China could promise in principle to grant land 
along the airport railway for auction, but it should be included 
in the annual disposal programme, senior Chinese representative 
of the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group, Guo Fengmin, said 
yesterday. 
  Britain wants to see the 62 hectares granted in one go. 
  "We have adopted a positive attitude towards the land 
disposal programme. But this is not what they called granting 
in one go," Mr Guo said. 
  The Director of the State Council's Hong Kong and Macao 
Affairs Office, Lu Ping, has said China can agree to grant the 
land along the airport railway over the next three years. 
However the final annual land grant had to be approved by the 
Land Commission. 
  But Mr Guo was optimistic. "I think an agreement will be 
reached very soon," he said. 
  Pressure for a deal will increase next week, when the 
influential Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce visits Beijing 
to put across the importance of an early agreement on the 
airport's financing. 
  "We will explain the adverse impact on the Hong Kong economy 
and that of southern China by delays to Hong Kong's vital 
infrastructure projects," said the leader of the delegation Paul 
Cheng Ming-fun. 
  Delay in the completion of Chek Lap Kok would result in lost 
revenue of $5.8 billion in 1997 alone, he said. The chamber 
will also argue for an early decision on the construction of 
Container Terminal No 9. 
  Mr Cheng said growing concerns about the slow progress of 
the work of the Joint Liaison Group, especially on the 
localisation of Hong Kong laws, would also be raised. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

