<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More on Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2705152794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1504 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2705152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 27 (XINHUA) -- A U.S. Embassy official 
has confirmed that the ASSOCIATED PRESS (AP) story on May 21 
claiming that China is "exporting prison-made products to the 
United States" was groundless, said an executive from the 
Chinese Ministry of Justice here today. 
  In accordance with relevant articles of the Memorandum of 
Understanding on the Prohibition of Import and Export of 
Prison-Made Products, signed by the Chinese Government and the 
U.S. Government, Chinese judicial departments arranged a visit 
by two officials from the U.S. Embassy in Beijing to the No. 4 
prison in east China's Zhejiang Province and other units from 
May 19 to 21. Prison officials answered questions from the U.S. 
officials and provided them with relevant materials. 
  There was no evidence during their visit that shows China 
had 
violated the memorandum of understanding, the ministry official 
said. 
  However, in his article AP reporter John Leicester claimed 
that "U.S. officials had information that the camps were 
exporting prison-made goods to the United States..." 
  In reponse to a Chinese Ministry of Justice official's 
inquiries, Lorraine Toly, first secretary for press of the U.S. 
Information Service of the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, said in a 
letter yesterday that AP reporter John Leicester had made 
"errors" in his article. 
  She said that "what I said was that if U.S. customs 
officials 
receive information that a Chinese prison might be exporting 
prison- made goods to the United States, they then contact the 
Chinese authorities to ask to inspect the prison. 
  "This explanation became in his article: `Toly said U.S. 
officials had information that the camps were exporting 
prison-made goods to the United States...'" 
  The U.S. official said: "I was annoyed by this article when 
I 
read it last week." She said: "I will call ASSOCIATED PRESS and 
complain." 
  In the letter, she also said that she was "sorry for any 
confusion this article might have caused." 
  The Justice Ministry official stressed that the Chinese 
Government has been implementing the Sino-U.S. memorandum on the 
prohibition of import and export of prison-made goods in a 
serious, responsible and effective way. 
  He pointed out that the letter from the U.S. Embassy 
official 
showed that the May 21 AP report by John Leicester was a sheer 
distortion of facts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51472 </DOCNO>
