<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources See `Restrained' PLA Reaction to Arms Import Ban </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sources See `Restrained' PLA Reaction to Arms Import Ban </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2805052494 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 
28 May 94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> HK2805052494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Willy Wo-lap Lam] </F>
  [Excerpt] The powerful People's Liberation Army [PLA] 
establishment has responded angrily to President Bill Clinton's 
ban on guns and ammunition, indicating it is yet another example 
of American "hegemonism". 
  Sources close to the army said, however, because the value 
of 
the targeted imports was no more than U.S.$200 million 
(HK$1.5-billion [Hong Kong dollars] ) the PLA would be 
relatively restrained in making public protests. 
  Moreover, the PLA is still hopeful of the resumption of full 
ties between the Chinese and the American armies, which would 
enable China to import technology with military applications. 
Diplomatic sources said the ban should not jeopardise the first 
steps that had been taken earlier this year towards the partial 
resumption of military links. 
  Chinese Vice-Chief of Staff General Xu Huizi is still 
expected to visit the U.S. in the summer, when he will probably 
look at military-related technology. The sources said that if 
the American army proved amenable to upgrading military 
relations, Beijing would not play up the just-announced ban. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

