<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Express Satisfaction With `Effective Cooperation' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Express Satisfaction With `Effective Cooperation' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2905095094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0941 GMT 29 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2905095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 29 (XINHUA) -- Both China and Russia 
have expressed their satisfaction over the "effective 
cooperation" in political, economic, scientific, cultural, 
military spheres and in maintaining public order over the past 
years and wished to expand and strengthen their cooperations in 
all these fields. 
  This was stated in a press communique on Russian Prime 
Minister V.S. Chernomyrdin's China visit issued today. 
  The prime minister left Dalian for home late today after 
concluding his four-day official visit to China, during which he 
also made his stay in Beijing and Shanghai. 
  The prime minister met with Chinese President Jiang Zemin 
and 
held talks with Chinese Premier Li Peng, extensively exchanging 
views on bilateral relations and some international issues of 
mutual interest. The visit has turned out to be quite a 
success, the communique says. 
  Both sides which have promised to stick to the principles 
laid down in the joint statement on December 18, 1992, are 
determined to set their eyes on the 21st century to move the 
Sino-Russian relations to a new high. The 1992 joint statement 
provides the base for Sino-Russian relations. 
  It is a common belief that the maintaining of a long-term, 
stable and good neighborhood relations characteristic of mutual 
beneficial cooperations accords with the fundamental interest of 
the two countries and peoples and constitutes an important 
factor in promoting peace, stability and development in the 
Asia-Pacific region and the world as a whole, the communique 
says. 
  Advancing the cooperations in economic, trade and scientific 
and technological fields is the main theme of the talks between 
the leaders. While acknowledging the positive achievements in 
the fields over the past years, both sides held that there are 
huge potentials in developing the Sino-Russian economic ties and 
trade, bases on the advantages of bordering each other and the 
supplementary economies of the two countries. In this aspect, 
the two sides agreed to participate in the construction of some 
bilateral and multi-lateral projects, including "continental 
bridge" linking Europe and Asia. 
  During the visit, the two countries signed seven cooperation 
agreements, including those on border management, marine 
transport, natural resources protection and fishery resources 
protection in the water areas bordering the two countries. 
  The two countries will also continue to strengthen their 
military technology-related cooperation under the conditions of 
sticking to and abiding by international obligations as agreed 
by the two countries, the communique says. 
  The two sides gave positive appraisal to the ongoing 
negotiations on borders and on cutting military presence in the 
border areas and enhancing mutual trust in the military field 
and held an agreement on the latter will be of important 
significance to enhancing mutual understanding and mutual trust 
between the two countries and to maintaining peace and stability 
in the Asia-Pacific region. China will stick to the provisions 
provided in the agreement on the eastern section of the 
Sino-Russian border while being willing to continue the talks on 
other left-over border issues and speeding up the preparation 
for the agreement on western section of the borders. 
  In exchanging views on reforming the economic structures, 
the 
two sides shared quite a few common points of view with regard 
to the process of the reform. Despite the different conditions 
of the two countries, introductions of each other's theories and 
practice in the economic reform will be of mutual benefit. 
  On the current international situation and some major 
international issues, leaders of the two countries held 
identical or similar views in many aspects, agreeing to 
reinforce constructive cooperations in regional and 
international affairs and to trigger mutual promotion in 
participating the Asia-Pacific economic cooperation. 
  Both sides agreed to continue and develop the positive 
dialogues at all levels including those at the highest level. 
In this aspect, the Russian prime minister invited Chinese 
Premier Li Peng to pay an official visit to Russia in 1995, 
which was accepted by Li Peng with pleasure. 

</TEXT>

