<H3> <TI>   Over 2,500 PBS Members Quit, Join Akar Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Over 2,500 PBS Members Quit, Join Akar Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2604135494 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 25 
Apr 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> BK2604135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kota Marudu, Sun -- More than 2,560 former Parti 
Bersatu Sabah [Sabah United Party, PBS] members quit the party 
to join the Angkatan Keadilan Rakyat, Akar, [People's Justice 
Organization), a state Barisan Nasional [BN] component, here 
today. 
  They submitted their membership forms to Akar president 
Datuk 
Mark Koding at the community centre. 
  They decided to join the Dusun-Kadazan based Akar after 
Bandau MP George Sangkin left the Parti Demokratik Sabah (PDS) 
[Sabah Democratic Party] to join the party last week. Sangkin 
was with PBS before joining PDS. 
  At the gathering, Koding called on members of the PBS, PDS, 
and Parti Bersatu Rakyat Sabah (PBRS) [Sabah United People's 
Party] to join Akar. 
  He said the party has set a target of increasing its members 
to 150,000 from the present 50,000 by the end of the year. 
  "Akar being a BN component is in a better position to 
champion the interests of the Dusuns and Kadazans [ethnic 
groups]," Koding said. 
  He said the newly-formed BN state government was sincere in 
wanting to develop the state. 
  "If we continue to isolate ourselves then we would be left 
behind from the mainstream of national development." 
  Akar deputy president and Minister of Culture, Youth and 
sports Pandikar Amin Mulia and Sangkin were also present at the 
function. 

</TEXT>

