<H3> <TI>   Saudi Arabia Urges Renewed Talks on Oil Project </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saudi Arabia Urges Renewed Talks on Oil Project </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904002994 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2904002994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yomei Tsuji] </F>
  [Text] Riyadh, 24 Apr -- Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of 
Keidanren [Japan Federation of Economic Organizations], who is 
currently visiting Saudi Arabia, met separately with Saudi 
Arabian Foreign Minister Saud al-Faysal bin Abd al-Aziz Al Saud, 
Petroleum and Mineral Resource Minister Hisham Muhyi al-Din 
Nazir, and other government officials in Riyadh city on 24 
April. During these meetings, Saudi Arabia expressed strong 
dissatisfaction with the fact Japan completely canceled the 1 
trillion yen joint-venture project to transport crude oil to 
Japan for refining last year, and urged resumption of 
negotiations. Nazir said: "Japan should allow Saudi Arabia to 
participate in subsidiary sectors of the oil business, such as 
refining, in Japan. We are greatly disappointed with Japan's 
withdrawal." Foreign Minister Saud, a member of the royal 
family, also touched on the withdrawal from the project, and 
said: "It is disappointing because we expected much from this 
project." 
  The project involves a joint venture of three Japanese 
companies--Nippon Oil Co. Ltd., Nikko Kyoseki Company (presently 
Japan Energy Company), and Arabian Oil Co. Ltd.--and their Saudi 
Arabian counterpart to build oil refineries in Japan to refine 
Saudi Arabian crude oil and sell the finished products in Japan. 
However, Japan judged this project was not profitable and 
informed Saudi Arabia of its decision to cancel in November last 
year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

