<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kakizawa Views Right of Collective Self-Defense </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakizawa Views Right of Collective Self-Defense </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3004132794 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3004132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On the issue of North Korean nuclear arms 
development, Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa stressed on 29 April 
that Japan needs to "deal with the situation within the scope of 
the Constitution." At the same time, he disclosed his view that 
Japan needs to give logistics support to the U.S. military 
should the United Nations decide to impose economic sanctions 
against North Korea. Moreover, on the government's 
interpretation--which prohibits the use of the right of 
collective self-defense--of the Constitution, Kakizawa said: 
"Will such an interpretation allow the Japan-U.S. security 
treaty to function well in dealing with an emergency? The 
people need to talk about it. It is about time for us to review 
the issue." In this way, he disclosed his view that the people 
should discuss interpretation of the Constitution in a direction 
to approve the use of the right of collective self-defense. He 
made these comments during an Asahi TV program. 
  Regarding the right of collective self-defense, Atsushi 
Kanda, director general of the Defense Agency [DA], suggested on 
28 April that there is a possibility that Japan may need to 
change its interpretation of the Constitution. On how Japan 
will deal with the North Korean issue, the ruling 
coalition--while giving consideration to the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ], which attaches importance to the limit of 
the Constitution--reached an agreement, saying, "Japan will be 
prepared for an emergency situation within the scope of the 
Constitution." However, ministers in charge of diplomatic and 
security policies made comments one after another on the right 
of collective self-defense. It seems that they made the remarks 
to suggest a possibility that the Hata administration, following 
the SDPJ's secession from the government, will start to review 
the government's interpretation of the Constitution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51505 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas084__a94009" </HT>


