<H3> <TI>   New Cabinet Members Discuss Current Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Cabinet Members Discuss Current Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    MITI Chief Hata Comments </H4>

<F P=102> OW2904145294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Apr 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2904145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Eijiro Hata, minister of international trade </F>
and industry, by unidentified NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 
correspondent; place and date not given; from the "Interview 
With Hata Cabinet Members in Charge of Economic Matters" series; 
one of two interviews comprising first part of series: "All 
Hata Cabinet Members Will Work To Defuse Japan-U.S. Friction"; 
first paragraph is introduction] 
  [Text] The Hata cabinet was inaugurated on 28 April. How 
will it tackle economic tasks such as early enactment of the 
1994 fiscal budget and the resumption of the stalled Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks? NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN has interviewed 
Eijiro Hata, minister of international trade and industry, on 
how he intends to carry out these pressing policies. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Are there any prospects for resuming 
the stalled Japan-U.S. economic framework talks? 
  [Hata] The cooperative system between Japan and the United 
States is important for the world economy, so all members of the 
Hata cabinet will work towards resuming the stalled framework 
talks. Although the Japanese Government is trying to conclude 
the framework talks prior to the Naples summit, I intend to use 
every contact with U.S. Government officials as an opportunity 
to discuss ways to resume the stalled talks. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] The United States imposes one-sided 
sanctions against Japan. What do you think of this U.S. posture? 
  [Hata] Neither Japan nor the United States should engage in 
eccentric action. Now that moves are afoot worldwide to create 
the World Trade Organization (WTO), Japan should have a candid 
exchange of views with the United States in order to dissuade 
the latter from invoking the Super 301 provision against Japan. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How do you think Japan should deal 
with North Korea's suspected development of nuclear weapons? 
  [Hata] Japan needs to cooperate with any decisions made by 
the United Nations. Since North Korea intends to settle the 
issue through dialogue, it is premature to discuss specific ways 
to resolve the issue. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How are you going to promote 
deregulation? 
  [Hata] The Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
[MITI] is being asked to press ahead with deregulation. MITI 
needs to make further efforts towards deregulation. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How do you see Japan's economy? When 
do you anticipate Japan's economy recovery? 
  [Hata] Housing and certain commercial electrical goods are 
showing favorable indicators, but Japan's economy is still mired 
in recession. The budget has a great effect on the economy, so 
I want to get a budget bill for fiscal 1994 enacted in the Diet 
at the earliest possible date. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] There is growing criticism that the 
bureaucracy is conspicuously controlling the policy decision 
process. 
  [Hata] Such criticism attests to the excellence of Japanese 
bureaucrats. While bureaucrats have expert knowledge, 
politicians make their decisions based on broad perspective. 
Politicians and political parties decide on policy matters and 
take responsibility for what they decide. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Do you have concrete measures to 
reduce Japan's trade surplus? 
  [Hata] Japanese private enterprises are largely responsible 
for Japan's surplus trade. I doubt the administration set 
certain numerical targets for reducing Japan's trade surplus. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What do you think of the controversy 
over the resignation of former Industrial Policy Bureau chief 
Naito? 
  [Hata] Personnel changes are to turn the bureaucratic 
mentality around and make bureaucrats carry out their duties in 
a fair and neutral manner. MITI has tried to conduct personnel 
changes in that manner since Naito's resignation triggered the 
controversy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51512 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas084__a94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-084-A </AU>
