<H3> <TI>   New Cabinet Members Discuss Current Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Cabinet Members Discuss Current Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kumagai on UN Support </H4>

<F P=102> OW0105121894 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0105121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In an interview with MAINICHI SHIMBUN and other 
media on 30 April, Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai 
commented on how Japan will deal with a possible UN decision to 
impose economic sanctions over the issue of the DPRK's (North 
Korea) nuclear arms development, saying: "We will abide by a UN 
decision because Japan is a member nation. At the same time, 
however, we have no choice but to act within the scope of the 
Constitution." However, he avoided to comment on the issue of 
the Self-Defense Forces' support activities, such as providing 
supplies to the U.S. military's naval blockade, saying: "Since 
I am a member of the government, I have to be careful about this 
issue." On the government's policy that use of the right of 
collective self-defense is contrary to the Constitution, Kumagai 
said that "there is no need to change the interpretation of 
previous administrations." 
  Moreover, on the coalition's policy to do its best to enact 
a 
rezoning bill for the single-seat and proportionate 
representation system by having discussions during the current 
Diet session, Kumagai said: "We quite agree with this idea." 
He stressed that the bill should be approved even if the 
government has to extend the Diet session. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51514 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas084__a94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-084-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Cabinet Urged To Implement Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Cabinet Urged To Implement Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0105141594 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0105141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by columnist Naoki Tanaka: "Deregulation Should Be </F>
Made the Top Priority Task of the Hata Cabinet"] 
  [Text] As long as the Hata cabinet is starting out as "a 
reform government"--although of a minority ruling coalition--it 
should announce its basic policy on reform to people at home and 
abroad. One of the important goals of reform should be the 
abolition of unreasonable economic regulations. The former 
Hosokawa government adopted an "administrative reform outline," 
and the key point of it was to abolish the regulations. The 
Hata administration is responsible for taking this over and 
implementing it. 
  As a way of implementing it, I hope, Prime Minister Tsutomu 
Hata will issue instructions to individual cabinet members on 
the need for deregulation and will evaluate all of his cabinet 
members based on how the deregulation program has been achieved. 
In case regulatory government offices want to leave some 
regulations as exceptions, they must once again explain reasons 
for them to the people. Otherwise, the people will not support 
the minority ruling coalition. 
  In the tax system reform, what must come first is the 
reengineering (drastic renovation of business operations) of the 
government sector through deregulation; nonessential expenses in 
the government sector should be cut down through deregulation 
and other actions. If reengineering is done successfully, it 
will become possible to raise the consumption tax only by a 
small rate. 
  The former administration set forth the concept of the 
national welfare tax. Assumptions made on the scale of tax rate 
increase at that time should change if the deregulation and 
administrative reengineering are going to be implemented. The 
taxpayers will not be able to understand a hike in the 
consumption tax, which is based on "rough estimates" and does 
not take this point into account. 
  In a policy of the coalition adopted before the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan bolted, it was agreed to "work out a 
decision on the tax reform--basically increasing the ratio of 
the indirect tax--by the end of June." But if regulations are 
to be drastically revised, it will be impossible to reach a 
decision on the tax system reform, including the consumption tax 
hike, by the end of June. What the government should do is keep 
income tax cuts in effect even after 1995, continue deregulating 
until the economy recovers, and pursue the tax system reform 
plan, including the consumption tax hike. 
  What is noteworthy in the new cabinet lineup is that Komeito 
produced posts and telecommunications minister, transport 
minister, and construction minister and that it thus has become 
an important component in the government. But these are posts 
of ministries known for having so many regulations. Will these 
three ministers be able to push on with deregulation? The 
public will come to find out the party's true stand on it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51515 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas084__a94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-084-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bureaucrats Discuss Hata Cabinet Lineup </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bureaucrats Discuss Hata Cabinet Lineup </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3004052794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3004052794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On the launching of the Hata government of minority 
parties, the bureaucrats of Kasumigaseki, Tokyo, in general 
think: "With its fragile base, the cabinet will have trouble 
pursuing reform policies." The political situation is likely to 
become insecure, and there is spreading concern regarding 
matters like North Korea over which the ruling and opposition 
parties are expected to differ. According to an official of the 
Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry, and Fisheries [MAFF]: "Now 
the Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] has returned to the 
opposition camp, the bureaucrats' power might become weaker than 
under the Hosokawa government." An official of the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry [MITI] admitted: "If the 
Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] and the SDPJ get together, the 
Diet will become shaky; it will be difficult to implement 
policies." 
  The Hosokawa government, which had the SDPJ on its side, was 
able to actively pursue policies on rice market liberalization 
and programs on the taxation system and pension reform, led by 
bureaucrats, but under the new government there is concern 
because "it is unclear how the SDPJ will act," as an official of 
the Ministry of Health and Welfare noted. 
  Another official of the MAFF said: "It will become difficult 
for us to work not only on opposition parties but also on ruling 
parties; it will not be easy to implement policies." There are 
also many who think that with the birth of the new coalition 
government a change will occur in the present trend of 
"bureaucrats having more power than politicians." 
  But as far as such issues as Japan-U.S. relations--an area 
where there are almost no policy differences between the ruling 
and opposition parties--are concerned, an official of the 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs [MOFA] said: "All we have to do is 
continue to do the things we were doing." Officials of MOFA are 
pleased to have Koji Kakizawa as their new minister, saying, "It 
should be easy to work with him since he is familiar with 
foreign affairs." 
  Likewise, the Economic Planning Agency has many expectations 
of its new director general, Yoshio Terazawa, who is well versed 
in economics and known for his "fine background" including his 
time as president of Nomura Securities U.S.A. (according to a 
senior official of the agency). Meanwhile, the Ministry of 
Finance, which has the task ahead of reforming the taxation 
system, is happy that its minister will remain in post. Vice 
Minister Jiro Saito said: "He is my senior as a bureaucrat, and 
we can work like one man." 
  The views of ministries differ regarding the fact that the 
Hata government strongly favors Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] 
members. 
  In MITI, which experienced the "incident of intervention" by 
former MITI Minister Kumagai to remove a senior official, the 
general response was: "The man whom the vice ministers have to 
watch closely has changed from Kumagai (known to be close to 
Ozawa) to Hata (known to be close to Prime Minister Hata); we 
should be able to work with him better." 
  In the case of the Ministry of Transport, which has a new 
minister from Komeito, the picture was one of relieved ministry 
officials. The officials said: "If we had someone from 
Shinseito, we would have the difficult problem of what distance 
we should maintain with Shinseito on the one hand, and with the 
LDP on the other." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

