<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shinseito Members Criticize Ozawa Leadership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shinseito Members Criticize Ozawa Leadership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3004011194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3004011194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Open criticism, which is unusual, erupted against 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] leadership at a Dietmen's caucus 
on 27 April. This followed reports that party Secretary General 
Ichiro Ozawa and a handful of party leaders had decided on a new 
position on the question of the new parliamentary group 
"Kaishin," which was the major reason why the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan's [SDPJ] bolted from the coalition government. 
Most of the Shinseito Diet members, even party executives, had 
not been informed of the decision. 
  It was an eruption of discontent about the way a small 
number 
of senior executives like Ozawa have made decisions unilaterally 
on policies and Diet operation matters in the past. 
  The man who opened the verbal attack was first-term Dietman 
Kiyoshi Ueda. He asked for an explanation from party officials: 
"The news media report that a retraction of the concept of 
`Kaishin' is being considered. What is going on?" Acting 
Secretary General Kozo Watanabe replied: "No such thing is 
being talked about. We are now making final efforts to have the 
SDPJ return to the coalition government." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51518 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas084__a94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-084-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Fujii on Economic Issues, Taxes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Fujii on Economic Issues, Taxes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904145494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2904145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Minister of Finance Hirohisa Fujii by </F>
unidentified NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN correspondent; place and date 
not given; from the "Interview With Hata Cabinet Members in 
Charge of Economic Matters" series; second of two interviews 
comprising first part of series; "Improvements Being Made in 
Substantiating the Consumption Tax"] 
  [Text] [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What do you think of the 
current economic situation? 
  [Fujii] We are in a very delicate stage. Economic 
indicators in some areas are good; in other areas, they are not 
so good. We need to make the economy grow for we are at an 
important stage. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] It is said that deliberations on the 
fiscal 1994 budget will be delayed. 
  [Fujii] It should not have a negative impact on people's 
everyday life. I will ask the Diet to start budget 
deliberations as soon as possible. I know we have a system 
which is supplementary to a tentative budget. However, it is 
too early for us to talk about it now. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] The minority ruling government needs 
the cooperation of both the Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] and 
the Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] to achieve tax 
reform. 
  [Fujii] A considerable number of people are beginning to 
understand that we have no choice but to reduce the income tax 
and substantiate the consumption tax in order to prepare for an 
aging society. We are beginning to share common views with the 
SDPJ. We have no choice but to seek the understanding of the 
people and the parties. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Do you no think that a compromise, 
such as changing the consumption tax to welfare tax, is needed 
for the coalition to achieve the other parties' understanding? 
  [Fujii] Many people protested against an earmarked tax 
[mokuteki zei] when the consumption tax was introduced. Many 
are still against it. We may use the revenue from this tax 
mainly for welfare services, but I do not know about an 
earmarked tax. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Do you not think administrative 
reform is needed to increase taxes? 
  [Fujii] We have been seriously trying to achieve 
administrative reform. The ruling parties are still meeting on 
it. I hope they will come up with concrete ideas and not 
abstract plans. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How about foreign exchange markets? 
  [Fujii] The fundamental of foreign exchange is to reflect 
the fundamentals [as published]. This was confirmed at a 
meeting of the finance ministers and central bank presidents 
from the group of seven (G-7) industrial nations. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Is the appreciation of the yen 
natural because the trade surplus is a fundamental? 
  [Fujii] I do not think so. The trade surplus is merely one 
item. I am sure the interest rate level, economic trends, and 
unemployment rates are also fundamentals. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How are you going to tackle the 
Japan-U.S. framework talks? 
  [Fujii] It is important for us to get the economic recovery 
back on track by promoting the current economic management plans 
in order to settle the issue. It is also important for 
international society to seek economic harmony. We have been 
trying to ease regulations regarding insurance and financial 
services. In addition, we also need to ease other regulations 
as well to act in harmony with international society. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

