<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kumagai Interviewed on Current Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kumagai Interviewed on Current Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305090694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0305090694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai by </F>
unidentified YOMIURI SHIMBUN correspondent; place and date not 
given] 
  [Text] [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] What are the tasks assigned to 
the new government? 
  [Kumagai] We have to pass the budget bill through the lower 
house as soon as possible. Japan and the United States must 
reach an agreement on the economic framework talks before the 
Naples summit in July. It is also hoped that suspicions 
attached to North Korea's development of nuclear weapons will 
eventually be cleared through peaceful negotiations; however, if 
the United Nations decides on imposing sanctions, we will 
cooperate within constitutional limits. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Do you mean the government's conventional 
view that the Constitution does not recognize the right to 
collective defense remains unchanged? 
  [Kumagai] It is not necessary for the new cabinet to change 
the government's long-held views. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] What do you think about criticism of the 
existence of a dual power structure? 
  [Kumagai] It is important for the prime minister to perform 
his duties using good judgment while increasing the openness of 
the decisionmaking process in his administration. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Do you see any possibility of a 
dissolution of the lower house and a general election under the 
current multiple-seat constituency system? 
  [Kumagai] The Diet adopted a bill on a new electoral system. 
A dissolution of the lower house under the current electoral 
system would reverse the wheels of history. We have to avoid 
that. The next lower house election should be held under the 
newly adopted electoral system. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] How will the government promote discussion 
of the tax reform issue? 
  [Kumagai] Discussions of tax reform would serve as an 
important step toward mending tattered relations with the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] and bringing the party back 
into the coalition. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] What are the prospects for restoring 
coalition ties with the SDPJ? 
  [Kumagai] There are points we have to reflect on, such as 
procedural mistakes. With this in mind, we have to talk 
persistently with the SDPJ to win its understanding. I believe 
the SDPJ will return to the coalition because the SDPJ agreed on 
basic coalition policies after thorough debate. We have to do 
our utmost to have the SDPJ back; otherwise, passage of our 
bills through the Diet will be impossible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51655 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085__a94005" </HT>


