<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   KDD Proposes Lower Inmalsat Service Fees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KDD Proposes Lower Inmalsat Service Fees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0158A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 Apr 94 
p 6--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0158A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] On 18 April, Kokusai Denshin Denwa (KDD) filed for 
approval of the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications to 
reduce charges for International Marine Satellite (Inmalsat) 
service and expansion of the time zone for discounted calls. The 
reduction in service charges were set at 12 to 18 percent with 
an implementation date of 1 May. They have decided to reduce 
rates based on economies of scale brought on by increased 
traffic and hope to gain further increases in utilization based 
on lower rates. 
  The current price cuts and expansion of discounted time 
zones 
will apply to marine satellite communications services offered 
to the Pacific and Indian Ocean regions via Inmalsat and the KDD 
Yamaguchi satellite station. 
  Price cuts will cover an 18-percent reduction for Inmalsat A 
which consists of analog telephone and facsimile services, 
12-percent reduction for digital Inmalsat B services, and 
13-percent reduction for Inmalsat M services involving 
miniaturized and lightweight marine vessel station facilities. 
As an example, a three-minute call on Inmalsat A services 
covering the Pacific and Indian Ocean regions formerly cost 
2,700 yen but will now cost 2,200 yen. 
  As for discounted time zones, they will be expanded from six 
to 10 hours for Inmalsat A and B services, and expanded an 
additional 10 hours for Inmalsat M services. 
  KDD first offered marine satellite communication services in 
1982 in the form of Inmalsat A services. Its services are now 
utilized by 1,300 Japanese vessels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51663 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085__a94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Urges Telecommunications Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Keidanren Urges Telecommunications Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0159A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Apr 94 p 
5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0159A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] On 19 April, Keidanren [Japan Federation of Economic 
Organizations] (Keidanren) completed recommendations calling for 
a review and maximum deregulation of information communications 
industries regulated by the government in areas such as 
telephone rate decisions and entry into class I electrical 
communication industries. The recommendations state that there 
is no special need to restrict market entry into the class I 
communications industries currently covered by NTT and 
Shindenden "because enormous capital investment requirements 
preclude the easy entry of new participants merely for the 
purpose of acquiring vested rights." Keidanren will work with 
the government to provide for incorporation of its 
recommendations in the government's information-communication 
deregulation plan to be completed by the end of June. 
  Keidanren also compiled an opinion paper concerning the 
construction of optical fiber cable networks in which the 
government is attempting initiatives which calls for 
"construction of optical fiber cable systems by private industry 
as a matter of principle" and for the government to provide 
assistance in the form of loans. 
  It appears that the government's Electrical Communication 
Council will complete a report in June which calls for the 
government to play a central role in the building of an optical 
fiber cable network for use as a new information communication 
network. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

