Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata on New Electoral System, Tax Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata on New Electoral System, Tax Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305125394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1245 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome, May 3 KYODO -- Japanese Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata said Tuesday [3 May] the next general election for 
the House of Representatives should be held under a new 
electoral system. 
  Hata, who arrived in Rome earlier in the day on the first 
leg 
of a six-day official visit to Italy, France, Germany and 
Belgium, said the prime minister's power to dissolve the lower 
house cannot be denied under any circumstances. 
  "However, looking into the reality, the Japanese people hope 
for an election under a new system. And basically, I am not 
thinking about dissolution now at all," Hata told Japanese 
reporters traveling with him. 
  Bills centered on a change in the lower house electoral 
system became law in late January. 
  Under the new system, 300 members are to be elected from 
single- seat constituencies and the remaining 200 through a 
proportional representation system. The present 511-seat lower 
chamber was elected from the multiseat constituencies. 
  But the new system will not take effect until the 
single-seat 
constituencies are delineated in several months. 
  Hata suggested it may take less than a three-month period 
for 
voters to learn the locations after they become law. 
  "Some people think it is easier to restore their power under 
the current system, but it is shameful to hold an election based 
on such thought," Hata said, referring to opinions of some 
members in the Social Democratic Party (SDP) [of Japan -- SDPJ] 
and new party Sakigake [Harbinger], both of which left the 
coalition recently. 
  The premier inaugurated a minority cabinet Thursday, after 
the SDP withdrew when other ruling parties formed a new 
parliamentary group, "Kaishin" (Innovation), without consulting 
the SDP. 
  "I will urge the SDP to reconsider. In apologizing for what 
happened, I want to appeal to the SDP before anything else," he 
said. 
  Hata also said he does not rule out the possibility of an 
alignment of his party, Shinseito, and the leading opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), but an appeal to the SDP takes 
precedence. 
  The LDP surrendered its 38-year grip on power last August, 
when it failed to maintain a majority in the lower house. 
  Sakigake, led by former Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi 
Takemura, was a coalition government member before it defected. 
It supports the Hata administration but refused to send 
personnel to his new cabinet. 
  In relation to North Korea's suspected nuclear arms program, 
Hata pledged that Japan will deal problems with care and "within 
the framework of the (war-renouncing) constitution." 
  His remark reflects caution on legislation to deal with 
emergencies, including possible international sanctions against 
North Korea. 
  Hata also said he will seek the public's acceptance of 
higher 
indirect taxes, saying, "A graying society is at hand. It will 
be difficult to secure necessary financial sources working only 
with income taxes." He declined to mention the amount or timing 
of a tax increase. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51674 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085_a_94007" </HT>


