<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Voters Polled on Support for Hata Cabinet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Voters Polled on Support for Hata Cabinet </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    TV Asahi, KYODO Polls Reported </H4>

<F P=102> OW0205151794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1412 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0205151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 2 KYODO -- The cabinet of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata got a 50.1 percent approval rating in a weekend 
poll of 662 voters, TV Asahi reported Monday [2 May]. 
  On Sunday, KYODO NEWS SERVICE's telephone poll of 1,000 
voters showed that 51.6 percent supported the Hata cabinet. 
  In Monday night's "News Station" program, TV Asahi said 31.9 
percent disapproved of the Hata cabinet, launched last Thursday. 
  Just before Hata was elected prime minister last Monday, the 
TV station conducted a similar survey which showed a 66.8 
percent approval rating for Hata's incoming cabinet. During the 
one-week period, the support rating fell 16.7 percentage points, 
TV Asahi said. 
  Following Hata's election in the Diet as Japan's 51st prime 
minister, the biggest coalition group, the Social Democratic 
Party (SDP), quit the alliance in protest against the swift 
formation of a large parliamentary group that excluded the SDP. 
  The TV Asahi poll also showed that 54 percent expressed 
support for the SDP's withdrawal from the coalition while 27 
percent disapproved of it. 
  Asked who is at the center of the new coalition, 52 percent 
named key coalition strategist Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general 
of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], while 21 percent nominated 
Hata who is Shinseito head and 4 percent picked former Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, head of the Japan New Party (JNP). 
  The poll also showed that 54 percent of pollees wanted the 
SDP to follow its own path, and 32 percent called for its 
cooperation with the Hata cabinet. Only 10 percent proposed the 
SDP cooperate with the largest opposition party, the Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP). 
  Asked how long the Hata cabinet will survive, 44 percent 
replied around half a year, followed by 23 percent who predicted 
three months and 18 percent one year or longer. The poll showed 
9 percent replied two months, and 2 percent one month. 
  It said 60 percent called for an early general election for 
the House of Representatives after the Diet passes the fiscal 
1994 budget, compared with 27 percent who did not. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51677 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085_a_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 May 1994 </DATE1>

