<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Voters Polled on Support for Hata Cabinet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Voters Polled on Support for Hata Cabinet </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    SANKEI SHIMBUN, Fuji TV Polls </H4>

<F P=102> OW0205034394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0132 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0205034394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 2 KYODO -- The new coalition cabinet of 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata scored a 62.1 percent support rating 
in a joint nationwide telephone survey by the SANKEI SHIMBUN and 
Fuji Television network published Monday [2 May]. 
  But nearly 70 percent of the 2,000 respondents called for an 
early general election in the wake of the pullout of the Social 
Democratic Party (SDP) [Social Democratic Party of Japan -- 
SDPJ] from the coalition, the SANKEI SHIMBUN said. 
  The public disapproval rate for the cabinet among the 
pollees 
was 17.6 percent, the newspaper said. 
  The public support rating of the Hata cabinet is 21.3 
percentage points lower than that of the cabinet of Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, Hata's predecessor, last August, but 
is still higher than the rating of previous cabinets of the 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), the newspaper said. 
  The support rate for the cabinet of Prime Minister Noboru 
Takeshita on its inauguration in November 1987 was 53 percent 
and that for the cabinet of Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa in 
November 1991 was 54.9 percent, the SANKEI said. 
  Of the 62.1 percent backing the Hata cabinet, 29.4 percent 
declared they support it unconditionally, while 32.7 percent 
said that if they have to choose, they support the newly 
launched cabinet, the SANKEI said. 
  The SANKEI and Fuji Television Network conducted the survey 
on Friday and Saturday. 
  Of the pollees, 45.1 percent cited pump-priming as the most 
important policy for the Hata cabinet, followed by 21.1 percent 
stressing tax reform, 14.9 percent political reform, and 8.4 
percent the rice issue, according to the SANKEI. 
  A large proportion -- 61.5 percent -- of the respondents 
support the pullout of the SDP from the coalition. 
  The LDP, the largest opposition party, garnered 22.3 percent 
support, followed by 11.3 percent for Shinseito [Japan Renewal 
Party], headed by Hata. 
  In a KYODO NEWS SERVICE public opinion poll released Sunday, 
the Hata cabinet posted a 51.6 percent public approval rating, 
down 24.1 percentage points from that for the Hosokawa cabinet 
last August. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

