<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `About Half' Diet Members Seek 2-Party System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `About Half' Diet Members Seek 2-Party System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305122794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1142 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 3 KYODO -- About half of Diet 
legislators surveyed want a two-party system in Japan's future 
politics, replacing the current multiparty setup, an influential 
private group promoting political reform said Tuesday [3 May]. 
  Of the lawmakers surveyed, 50.3 percent prefer a two-party 
system, 39.3 percent favor a moderate multiparty system with 
three or more parties, and 3.5 percent like a long and stable 
rule by a single party, according to a poll conducted by the 
Committee for the Promotion of Political Reform. 
  The group of dozens of voluntary members from business, 
labor, academic and journalistic circles sent questionnaires to 
761 lawmakers of both houses, 239 business executives and 78 
labor unionists from April 1 to 22, committee members said. Of 
the legislators, 59.5 percent responded, they said. 
  According to the survey, 20.3 percent of the lawmakers said 
most existing parties will disappear in political realignment. 
  As to the timing of such realignment, 58.6 percent of the 
Diet members said it will take place in a year and 12.4 percent 
said in several years, they said. 
  A two-party system was sought by 88.5 percent of respondents 
from Komeito [Clean Government Party], a Buddhist-backed party 
in the coalition, 87.3 percent from Shinseito [Japan Renewal 
Party], a key party led by Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, and 60.9 
percent from the Democratic Socialist Party, another ruling 
party, they said. 
  A moderate multiparty system was backed by 70.8 percent of 
members of the Japan New Party led by former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  The figure was identical for the Social Democratic Party, 
which defected the coalition last week, and 50 percent for new 
party Sakigake [Harbinger] led by former Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura. Sakigake refused to take new cabinet 
positions, they said. 
  The biggest opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) was 
split, with 45.6 percent favoring a two-party system and 41.8 
percent support a moderate multiparty system, they said. The 
LDP surrendered its 38-year grip on power last August. 
  Members of the opposition Japanese Communist Party did not 
answer the survey, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

