<H3> <TI>   Construction Minister on Public Works Projects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Construction Minister on Public Works Projects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804142294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1345 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Newly named Construction 
Minister Koji Morimoto said Thursday [28 April] he plans no 
change in the policy of the former government of Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa to boost Japan's public works projects program 
for the current decade. 
  "I think the program should be expanded. I want to study it 
more," he told reporters at a news conference, his first as 
construction chief. 
  The former Hosokawa government decided to add more projects 
to the 430 trillion yen program, which was set up in line with 
Japan's agreement on the structural impediments initiative (SII) 
talks with the United States concluded in June 1990. 

</TEXT>

