<H3> <TI>   Home Trading Via Multimedia System Studied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Home Trading Via Multimedia System Studied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704092594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0820 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704092594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 27 KYODO -- Japan's "big four" 
brokerage houses have started preparations for the use of 
multimedia system for home stock trading, industry officials 
said Wednesday [27 April]. 
  The officials said Daiwa Securities Co. has formed a team of 
experts to study ways to enable customers to engage in stock 
trading at home using the interactive system. 
  Customers can call up on the screen all necessary data, 
including the business results of interested firms and economic 
indexes while listening to advice from salespeople, they said. 
  Similar studies are being made by three other brokerages, 
including Nomura Securities Co., the officials said. 
  They said investors will be able to engage in stock trading 
at home when the multimedia system for home use is introduced. 
  The securities companies introduced home trading in 1988 
using television game machines, but the existing system cannot 
meet the needs of customers because the volume of information 
provided is limited. 

</TEXT>

