<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farm Group on Agriculture Reconstruction Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farm Group on Agriculture Reconstruction Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604141894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1139 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- The group governing 
agricultural cooperatives said Tuesday [26 April] it has drafted 
a proposal for agriculture reconstruction, centering on a review 
of the controversial Food Control Law. 
  The Central Union of Agricultural Cooperatives (Zenchu) said 
the proposal also calls on the government to increase stockpiles 
of rice, including imported rice, to about two million tons. 
  The union also urged the government to review its policy of 
rice production cutbacks under which farmers are imposed a 
uniform quota for acreage reduction. 
  The proposal is in line with the government policy of 
deregulation to cope with a partial opening of Japan's rice 
market, union officials said. 
  The officials said the union wants the government to adopt a 
pricing system aimed at promoting consumption of domestically 
produced rice. 
  Rice held in government stock should be used not only for 
table use but also for animal feeds and foreign aid, the 
officials said. 
  They said the government should seek the people's 
understanding for an extra cost of about 219.3 billion yen for 
the rice stockpiles. 
  The proposal will be examined further before it is submitted 
to the government on June 8, when the union will come up with 
its demand for prices of newly reaped rice this year, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

