<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   British Firm Signs Contract With Kelantan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    British Firm Signs Contract With Kelantan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0205145894 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 30 
Apr 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> BK0205145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Shamsul Akmar] </F>
  [Excerpt] Kota Baru, Fri. -- The PAS [Pan Malaysia Islamic 
Party]-led Kelantan Government will award a contract for its 
water supply project to a British company despite the Federal 
Government's decision not to give new contracts to British 
firms. Menteri Besar [Chief Minister] Nik Abdul Aziz Nik Mat 
said today the State Exco [executive council] met last week and 
decided to hire Thames Water for the project. 
  The ban on the award of government contracts for British 
firms was imposed on February 25 following unsubstantiated 
reports by the British media of alleged corruption on the part 
of Malaysian political leaders in deals involving British firms. 
The Cabinet had made it clear that the ban included all Federal 
and State Government contracts. 
  All State Governments, except for the Pas-led Kelantan State 
Government and the then PBS [Sabah United Party] Sabah State 
Government, had supported the move. The decision also received 
overwhelming support from various quarters in Malaysia, 
including politicians, trade unions, non-governmental 
organisations and individuals. Kelantan is the only State to go 
against the Federal Government's decision. 
  Nik Aziz said the project would be a joint venture between 
Thames Water and Yayasan Kelantan Darulnaim (Yakin). It would 
be carried out on a privatised basis and would be for the supply 
of water to the State's water treatment plants. 
  "We hope the project will overcome the acute water shortage 
we anticipate in a few years. In fact, we are already facing 
the problem and we have to do something fast to rectify the 
situation," Nik Aziz said. He neither, however, elaborated on 
why the State Government had decided to engage a British firm 
nor disclosed the terms and conditions of the deal. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

