<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Thinking of Japan-Korea Friendship' Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Thinking of Japan-Korea Friendship' Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0205104194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1014 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0205104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 30 [date as received] (KNS-KCNA) -- 
Japanese figures of different circles held a meeting for 
thinking of Japan-Korea friendship in Kyoto on April 23. 
  Speeches were made at the meeting attended by Azuma Okuda, 
chairman of the International Higher Institute; Hiroshi 
Wakabayashi, secretary general of the Japan Committee for 
Supporting the Independent and Peaceful Reunification of Korea; 
Hisateru Mitsuda, honorary professor at Kyoto University; and 
other political, public and academic figures and men of the 
press, 400 in all. 
  Liberal-democratic member of the House of Representatives 
Hiromu Nonaka in his speech charged that the Japanese ruling 
coalition was spreading anti-DPRK public opinion over the 
"nuclear problem" of the DPRK. 
  "The Japanese people" he said "should strive to make the 
relations with the DPRK very close ties and restore Japan- Korea 
friendship and confidence." 
  Prof. Motofumi Asai at Meijigakuin University in his speech 
pointed out that the United States is crying over the "nuclear 
problem" of DPRK for the purpose of putting down public opinion 
for disarmament at home. 
  Honorary Prof. Toshiyuki Toyota at Nagoya University in his 
speech said the Japanese media were distorting facts by quoting 
a part of Western reports and the International Atomic Energy 
Agency was applying a double-standard policy regarding the 
"nuclear problem" of the DPRK. 
  Lawyer Yoshihiro Sorano said that, in view of Japan-Korea 
friendship, the issue of postwar settlement must be solved 
properly and the conditions of the Koreans in Japan be improved. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

