<H3> <TI>   Foreign Party Leaders Support Nation's Struggle </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Party Leaders Support Nation's Struggle </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK3004112894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1029 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3004112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 30 (KCNA) -- The Central Committee 
of the Workers' Party of Korea received solidarity messages from 
foreign parties and party leaders supporting the Korean people's 
struggle for defending the dignity of their nation and the 
sovereignty of their country. 
  The messages came from Jean Pierre Ngambi, general secretary 
of the Communist Party of Cameroon, Eduardo Mora Valverde, 
convenor of the Central Committee of the People's Party of Costa 
Rica, Humberto Vargas Carbonel, secretary general of the Central 
Committee of the People's Vanguard of Costa Rica, Stevan 
Mirkovic, president of the League of Communists of Yugoslavia, 
Otete Gaston Mboyo, national chairman of the National Movement 
of the Genuine Lumumbist Combatants of Zaire, the National 
Executive Committee of the Communist Party of the Congo and the 
Central Committee of the Galicia People's Union of Spain. 
  The National Executive Committee of the Communist Party of 
the Congo in its message expressed full support to the just 
measure taken by the DPRK Government to defend the security and 
sovereignty of the country. It contended that the nuclear issue 
of Korea should be solved through DPRK-USA negotiations, not by 
means of "sanctions" or pressure. 
  The message from Zaire urged that the United States should 
immediately stop all its crafty moves to provoke another war on 
the Korean peninsula and that the International Atomic Energy 
Agency should act with discretion in accordance with its mission 
as a genuine scientific organization. 
  The general secretary of the Communist Party of Cameroon in 
his message demanded a prompt halt to all the attempts to lead 
the situation on the Korean peninsula to the brink of a war. 

</TEXT>

