<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S.-Tokyo Talks on DPRK Issue Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S.-Tokyo Talks on DPRK Issue Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305043894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0416 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305043894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, May 2 KYODO -- Japan and the United 
States reconfirmed Monday [2 May] that they will continue to 
seek a negotiated solution to the controversy over North Korea's 
alleged nuclear weapons program "if at all possible," Japanese 
officials said. 
  In working-level defense talks at the Pentagon, Japan 
pledged 
to "fulfill its responsibilities within the constraints of the 
constitution" should the United Nations take measures such as 
economic sanctions to enforce its demand for full inspections of 
North Korean nuclear facilities. 
  Concerning the North Korean nuclear issue, Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata's minority government plans to stick to the 
policies of the coalition under former Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, Japanese defense officials told their U.S. 
counterparts. 
  Pentagon officials expressed concern over the standoff 
between Pyongyang and the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA), which has been demanding unhampered access to nuclear 
sites, including a radiochemistry laboratory, believed to be 
part of a covert weapon program. 
  They also pointed to the "extremely important" role of 
China, 
North Korea's traditional ally, in efforts to find a peaceful 
solution to the controversy. 
  Washington again raised its request for Japanese 
participation in its Theater Missile Defense (TMD) scheme, a 
scaled-down version of former U.S. President Ronald Reagan's 
Strategic Defense Initiative (SDI), but the Japanese delegation 
remained noncommittal. 
  They did, however, promise to "study" the proposal, 
including 
its "cost-effectiveness." 
  The U.S. officials also urged the quick conclusion of an 
agreement that would facilitate swapping material such as fuel 
and services between the U.S. forces stationed in Japan and the 
Japanese Self-Defense Forces (SDF). 
  Such an agreement would also benefit the SDF in future 
United 
Nations-led peacekeeping operations, the U.S. officials said, 
according to the Japanese officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51750 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085_a_94002" </HT>


