<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Pledges To Provide Grant-in-Aid to Egypt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Pledges To Provide Grant-in-Aid to Egypt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305122594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1204 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 3 KYODO -- Japan pledged Tuesday [3 May] 
to provide Egypt a total of 3.97 billion yen in grant-in-aid to 
cooperate in its projects to repair a tunnel and to improve 
medical services, the Foreign Ministry said. 
  Japan's new Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa, who is on a 
four- 
nation Middle East tour, exchanged documents on the Japanese 
assistance in Cairo with Egypt's Minister for International 
Cooperation Yusuf Butrus-Ghali, the ministry said. 
  The aid consists of up to 3.06 billion yen to cooperate in 
Egypt's project to rehabilitate the Ahmed Hamdi Tunnel [spelling 
as received] linking mainland Egypt and Sinai Peninsula, and 913 
million yen for a project to improve medical services in the 
hospitals in Upper Nile, it said. 
  The latest aid for the project to rehabilitate the tunnel is 
part of the 7.58 billion yen Japan has already pledged to 
provide over a four-year period beginning 1992, the ministry 
said. 
  The Ahmed Hamdi Tunnel was built in 1983 but its condition 
is 
deteriorating because of the corrosion of concrete, it said. 
  The 913 million yen will be used to purchase basic medical 
equipment for six public hospitals in Luxor city and the Qena 
Governorate, it said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

