<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Expects Continued `Watchlist' Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Expects Continued `Watchlist' Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0305041594 Bangkok THE NATION in English 3 May 94 p A3 </F>
<F P=103> BK0305041594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Commerce Minister Churin Laksanawisit said 
yesterday the U.S. trade watchdog is expected to keep Thailand 
on its watchlist after the annual revision of the list is 
announced today. 
  Churin said he was not optimistic that the U.S. Trade 
Representative (USTR) would remove Thailand from all watchlist 
categories, because "the U.S. is likely to wait until the Thai 
parliament passes the third reading of the amended Copyright 
Bill." 
  In response to an earlier report that the USTR had already 
removed Thailand from its priority watchlist (PWL) and moved it 
to the normal watchlist classification, Churin said the 
announcement had not been made. 
  An economic officer at the U.S. Embassy also confirmed that 
the USTR had yet to release an official statement. "I have not 
received any report from Washington," he said. The officer, 
however, noted that the USTR was at any moment expected to 
announce a revision of the countries on its trade watchlist. 
  Thailand last year was removed from the most serious 
classification, the priority foreign country (PFC) status, to 
the lesser PWL after Commerce Minister Uthai Phimchaichon 
assured the USTR that the Thai government would introduce a new 
copyright law soon. The new copyrights bill has yet to come 
into force, pending its third reading in Parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

