<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sends Second Letter to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sends Second Letter to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305002694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0013 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305002694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Berlin, May 2 (YONHAP) -- The International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA] sent another letter to North Korea Monday 
urging the communist state to let IAEA experts undertake 
inspections when it changes fuel rods at the 5-megawatt reactor 
in Yongbyon, sources close to the agency said. Such inspections 
are necessary under the nuclear safeguards agreement, the IAEA 
has reportedly pointed out. 
  The agency sent a second letter after determining that North 
Korea's reply on April 29 to its first letter was 
unsatisfactory. Monday's letter was sent to ascertain North 
Korea's true intentions, the sources said Tuesday. 
  In its reply, Pyongyang told the nuclear watchdog that the 
fuel rods at the 5-megawatt reactor must be changed soon and 
requested an early dispatch of IAEA inspectors. It made no 
commitment, however, on IAEA requests laid down as conditions 
for the presence of its inspectors at the refueling. North Korea 
only agreed to allow the inspectors to be present when it 
removes spent fuel rods from the reactor. 
  It gave no clear reply to "the IAEA's flexible technical and 
compromising plans" on taking samples in order to determine the 
extent of plutonium extraction and the reactor's operating 
condition. 
  The IAEA, in its initial letter sent early last week, told 
North Korea it was willing to compromise and take random samples 
of the spent rods, seal them and analyze them later. 
  Although the North Koreans themselves suggested that the 
IAEA 
be present during the refueling of the five-megawatt reactor, 
they have failed to make an offer that would allow satisfactory 
inspection activities, the sources said. As a result, the IAEA 
sent the second letter seeking to confirm North Korea's exact 
intentions, they added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51760 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085_d_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gap Said Narrowed on Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gap Said Narrowed on Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305052994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0514 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305052994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 3 (YONHAP) -- North Korea and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) have narrowed their 
differences enough to allow an inspection team to arrive in 
Pyongyang as early as this week, sources here said. 
  A letter sent by the agency Monday is expected to be their 
last communication, and the IAEA inspectors should be able to 
fly to North Korea as soon as Pyongyang responds, they said. 
  The two sides have been wrangling over the scope of the 
inspection of North Korea's 5-megawatt nuclear reactor. 
Scrutinizing the reactor's fuel rods would allow the U.N. 
nuclear watchdog to trace Pyongyang's secretive nuclear weapons 
program and estimate how much plutonium it has. 
  The sources said the IAEA is unlikely to conduct the 
inspections required to trace the program's history. However, 
the agency has compromised by agreeing to let North Korea seal 
the materials under IAEA monitoring for future inspection and 
analysis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

