<DOCNO> FBIS4-51761 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085_d_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Reportedly To Accept More Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Reportedly To Accept More Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305015594 Seoul SEOUL SINMUN in Korean 3 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305015594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul SEOUL SINMUN </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Pak Chong-hyon from Paris] </F>
  [Text] It was reported on 2 May 1994 that North Korea has 
made known to the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] its 
intention to accept additional inspections recommended by the UN 
Security Council presidential statement. 
  On 2 May, a high-ranking diplomatic source said: "Last 
weekend, North Korea told the IAEA that it was willing to accept 
additional inspections, including the taking of samples in the 
glove-box area and gamma mappings in the radiochemical 
laboratory, which it had not allowed during last March 
inspections." 
  The source added: "North Korea has clarified the reason for 
this, saying it will accept additional inspections, inasmuch as 
the ROK has recently shown a flexible attitude by withdrawing 
the condition on the exchange of special envoys between the 
North and South--a precondition to the U.S.-North Korean 
high-level talks. The IAEA is discussing measures as to North 
Korea's acceptance of additional inspections." 

</TEXT>

